responses.text:
Loss can be good for us—a paradox in bone,
The hollow ache reshapes us, carves new paths unknown.
In the hush of absence, seeds of wonder wake;
We gather up the pieces, rebuilt for our own sake.

A bird that leaves the nest, a tide that pulls away,
The empty spaces teach us what presence could not say.
Grief is not a failure, nor absence just a scar;
Loss can be good for us—revealing who we are.

So let us greet the breaking, the letting go, the fall;
For in the quiet aftermath, we find ourselves—after all.

Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
the velvet hush of midnight’s mist;
let wildflowers crown your tangled hair,
and secrets wander through the air.
Slip through gardens overgrown,
where laughter finds you all alone;
write your name in muddy streams,
dream bold and riotous dreams.
Go, quicksilver child, unfurl your bliss—
let every forbidden joy be this:
a fleeting touch, a stolen wish—
go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss.

Beneath the battered eaves, the world awaits a sign—
A cricket’s chirr, a lantern’s gleam, a subtle, daring line.
The clatter of young heels withheld, a silence thick and brief;
In this quiet intermission, dreams are nimble, mischief chief.
The scent of chalk and ink pervades the sleeping, hallowed stone;
Ghosts of laughter gathering, a kingdom all their own.
A prelude, yes—a heartbeat poised, before the storm unfurls;
A secret pact of brotherhood, in this small world of boys and whirls.
